ity of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  See  Denby  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Denby","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): habitational name from any of the places so named in Yorkshire. A cognate of   Danby  , ‘settlement of the Danes’, but here the Old Norse first element has been replaced by the cognate Old English <i>Dene</i>."]}]},{"name":"Wales","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Wales near Sheffield (South Yorkshire). The placename means ‘The Welshmen’ and denoted a settlement of Brittonic speakers living on the boundary between the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms of Northumbria and Mercia (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). See also   Wallis  .","habitational name from Wales, the country named from Old English <i>wēalas</i> ‘foreigners’ (especially those speaking Celtic or Romance languages). This meaning of the surname is quite rare."],"variants":[{"name":"Wailes","meanings":["English: variant of   Wales  ."]},{"name":"Wallis","meanings":["Scottish and English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>Waleis</i>, <i>Walais</i> ‘Welshman’, also sometimes ‘Breton’ (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning a ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). In western and central England the medieval reference is clearly to Welshmen. In Norfolk and Lincolnshire, the reference was probably to Bretons, many of whom settled in the eastern counties after the Conquest. Compare   Welsh  ,   Walsh  . The idea that the Scottish surname refers to the Welsh-speaking Britons of Strathclyde is erroneous."]}]},{"name":"Parish","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘lord of the monkeys’, used since medieval times as a byname of Vishnu."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"RUABON,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","variant of   Rathbone   with loss of medial <i>-th-</i>; see   Rathbun  .","nickname from northern Middle English <i>ra-bayn</i> (Old Norse <i>rá-bein</i> ‘roe-bone’ or ‘roe leg’), used for a man who could run as fast as a roe-deer."],"variants":[{"name":"Rathbone","meanings":["English: variant of   Rathbun  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Parish of  RUABON, Denbigh, Wales was born as the son of County of DENBIGHSHIRE, WALES. He had at least 58 sons."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1475–1520":"1475–1520","1492–Male":"1492–Surnud","1501–1608":"1501–1608","1515–Male":"1515–Surnud","1532–Male":"1532–Surnud","1533–1617":"1533–1617","1536–Male":"1536–Surnud","1623–Male":"1623–Surnud","1647–Male":"1647–Surnud","–1520":"–1520","–1540":"–1540","–1648":"–1648","1492":"1492","1536":"1536","1623":"1623","1501":"1501","1533":"1533","1532":"1532","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1608":"1608","1617":"1617","1648":"1648","1647":"1647","1515":"1515"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1475–1520":"1475–1520","1492–Male":"1492–Kuollut","1501–1608":"1501–1608","1515–Male":"1515–Kuollut","1532–Male":"1532–Kuollut","1533–1617":"1533–1617","1536–Male":"1536–Kuollut","1623–Male":"1623–Kuollut","1647–Male":"1647–Kuollut","–1520":"–1520","–1540":"–1540","–1648":"–1648","1492":"1492","1536":"1536","1623":"1623","1501":"1501","1533":"1533","1532":"1532","1520":"1520","